document.title: Colorado Department of Education 2019-2020 Academic Standards & EEOs

462EDB05CB6D42CD84D45DA5C47B8A6C.description: Modeling with Geometry: Apply geometric concepts in modeling situations.

1474085133134898B257BB143CFFA4DB.description:
Identify the shapes of two-dimensional cross-sections of three-dimensional
objects (EE.G.GMD.4).

267ED5752EB94A31AA89B1A4DCC73D09.description: Geometric Measurement and Dimension: Visualize relationships between two-dimensional and three-dimensional objects.

0C14F32EEB924D7AA6479F1C99D07135.description: Use volume formulas for cylinders, pyramids, and cones to solve problems.

B52C60A0C9884C878ABD63ADAC0F86B5.description:
Predict the circumference or area of a circle or the volume of a cylinder,
pyramid, or cone and then use a formula or model to test that prediction.

53E2A865E8074DA8941261E2F0F9858F.description: Geometric Measurement and Dimension: Explain volume formulas and use them to solve problems.

75A914876D1644D0BC4F8D965FEA9661.description:
Use coordinates and measure to find perimeters of polygons and areas of
triangles and rectangles.

BD8A4AC8687E48B398410138721BB9BF.description: Expressing Geometric Properties with Equations: Use coordinates to prove simple geometric theorems algebraically.

9B9A1C2CD6B14483BFA3AC378F0D5378.description:
Expressing Geometric Properties with Equations: Translate between the geometric description and the equation for a conic
section.

1E11B6AC4D164B16BB3EA78B641E43C9.description: Circles: Find arc lengths and areas of sectors of circles.

8311747882694FD88075EB6D39D68C62.description: Circles: Understand and apply theorems about circles.

8C8AA50C3F3D49A49E7BB77ADD8F395D.description: Similarity, Right Triangles, and Trigonometry: Apply trigonometry to general triangles.

08FBAEAC4D674C51BFFE28F01C29C060.description: Similarity, Right Triangles, and Trigonometry: Define trigonometric ratios and solve problems involving right triangles.

D29273D6642D4A8792214FAABA449E4E.description: Similarity, Right Triangles, and Trigonometry: Prove theorems involving similarity.

FA95E52A98A64CC6BCEF10A0CD8BDEE8.description: Similarity, Right Triangles, and Trigonometry: Understand similarity in terms of similarity transformations.

CDD3B13799404C5DA03A18A324F7C2FC.description:
Explain how every triangle with the same three length sides is congruent,
but the same is not true for every triangle with the same three angles.

8DFEE5C98B814F12A98927BB8D76A78C.description:
Show that two triangles are congruent by matching up their three pairs of
corresponding sides and three pairs of corresponding angles.

9AFE43EC30D34EC999EAB0820CF0E342.description:
Given a geometric figure, rotate (90, 180, or 270 degrees) or translate it a
given amount or reflect it over a given line of symmetry.

DD92F6D70F0846828F897C142C733194.description: Congruence: Understand congruence in terms of rigid motions.

5F59A07B5EC94D97937D3B56DF706A7B.description:
Given a geometric figure and a rotation, reflection, or translation of that
figure, identify the corresponding parts.

3089743C4DDF433895C6AA9489B632C3.description:
Describe rotations with an angle measure (90, 180, and 270 degrees),
reflections with a line of symmetry, and translations with a direction and
distance.

BEA8AE282955487A9E87243FC071FC38.description:
Know the attributes of perpendicular lines, parallel lines, line segments,
angles, and circles (EE.G-CO.1).

61C674DC4A8947BE82F270F8BB4E40A6.description: Congruence: Experiment with transformations in the plane.

4AC2D95EB46B43AC9CFE4B71DBF44E05.description: Using Probability to Make Decisions: Use probability to evaluate outcomes of decisions.

C9773400D648414193E43A0B72052AB9.description: Using Probability to Make Decisions: Calculate expected values and use them to solve problems.

40BD46490ABE448C95A07A1412B761FD.description:
Conditional Probability & the Rules of Probability: Use the rules of probability to compute probabilities of compound events in a
uniform probability model.

B1EA14DBC2084EE7AC372303EB769E69.description:
For example, recognize that the probability of flippind heads on a
second coin flip is independent of the first flip, but the probability of
being dealt an ace from a deck of cards depends on what cards have
already been dealt.

0DFA64388DC942CB91E010667300D104.description:
Recognize independent and dependent probability in everyday language
and everyday situations.

DAB36D018C194279A9A5AB330331D7C5.description:
Conditional Probability & the Rules of Probability: Understand independence and conditional probability and use them to
interpret data.

F319C2249BC0460F926F2BD1B9917979.description:
Making Inferences & Justifying Conclusions: Make inferences and justify conclusions from sample surveys, experiments, and
observational studies.

CBE306CB96E44FA190AE0DBB8DD31666.description:
For example, determine that the likelihood of a coin landing heads is 0.5
because there are two sides and each is equally likely to land facing up
(EE.S-IC.1-2).

75DDBCF7DF05470FA54D7D5E8CE0E745.description:
Determine the likelihood of an event occurring when the outcomes are
equally likely to occur.

8BDBF9DF02E34469958FC4EFF3F49F69.description:
For example, predict that the average height of all 10th graders is about
5 feet 7 inches if the average height of one class is about 5 feet 7 inches.

E0369604D0594BC2A2288504404EDD8B.description:
Demonstrate an understanding that a sample can tell us something about
the population it comes from.

07FCA8F3326F447E9AA60AB4A78DC700.description: Making Inferences & Justifying Conclusions: Understand and evaluate random processes underlying statistical experiments.

36756EF5835547A7A1D5B8C31963957F.description:
For example, a linear model y = 2x + 5 that fits a scatterplot of height of
a tree versus years since planting could represent an average growth of
2 feet per year and a height of 5 feet when initially planted.

E3D41C37BB7F4DDEB49E97B844EDF468.description:
Interpret the slope (rate of change) and the intercept (constant term) of a
linear model in the context of the data.

B93129DF14634B4486B44AA49F0C1A09.description: Interpreting Categorical & Quantitative Data: Interpret linear models.

32358AD59F4C42578BEBA2DCCC06EABF.description:
Informally fit a linear function for a scatter plot that suggests a linear
association.

F95250AF2E3443CE94593DC6304F5E4F.description:
Represent data on two quantitative variables on a scatter plot, and describe
how the variables are related.

A7103E0B63BE40BEB50D9B47BCB48336.description:
Interpreting Categorical & Quantitative Data: Summarize, represent, and interpret data on two categorical and quantitative
variables.

C52454683C0C42DC97410764F06E463A.description:
Calculate the mean of a given data containing up to at least five data points
(EE.S-ID.4).

4EDBEA08CBAB41FE859AB49553332724.description:
Interpret general trends about the center and spread of data given a graph
or chart.

14BB6FCBB4C94423BEFB5C423C26236D.description:
Use visual displays of data distributions with similar scales to judge which
distribution has the greater center and/or greater spread.

E9BC53F82E214B3EA9491A59D954AD6C.description:
Model data in context with plots on the real number line (dot plots,
histograms).

1063039D7E6B44929EFD45DA6CDB4D4C.description:
Interpreting Categorical & Quantitative Data: Summarize, represent, and interpret data on a single count or measurement
variable.

6BF3758DAE8B495FA41715E9FDBE496F.description: Trigonometric Functions: Prove and apply trigonometric identities.

A2811219F4254F5D930AA46FC211E6F7.description: Trigonometric Functions: Model periodic phenomena with trigonometric functions.

6CFAC2F4EF1F46D1B3ABD88EAC6239D8.description: Trigonometric Functions: Extend the domain of trigonometric functions using the unit circle.

BD667CCF79954F77BF0084A331A68D3C.description: Linear, Quadratic, & Exponential Models: Interpret expressions for functions in terms of the situation they model.

6E29EA3F119149668701D8290FB266F4.description:
Use graphs to describe a quantity increasing exponentially eventually
exceeds a quantity increasing linearly.

0924676521594AD180549ABA538A35FC.description:
Construct a linear function such as y + mx to show that these functions
increase by equal amounts over equal intervals.

2AAD7E628A0E402E91B3D74C3D2C48D1.description:
Distinguish between situations that can be modeled with linear functions
and with exponential functions.

62CDDB79B85F4845A659E4E1CC5262E0.description: Linear, Quadratic & Exponential Models: Construct and compare linear, quadratic, and exponential models and solve problems.

893BF2B3661C47DCACDC1AE0EA74A4E0.description: Building Functions: Build new functions from existing functions.

D8B379B297CA4A6FAEFB014EE93A7167.description:
Write or select arithmetic and geometric sequences of whole numbers that
match a given recursive rule.

B237F151713C48AE8787D5E15D7D6355.description:
Write or select a function that describes a relationship between two
quantities.

3098870F438440078362211ABBA8F6B3.description: Building Functions: Build a function that models a relationship between two quantities.

BDCCA38EE00149BE813EAFECDA817157.description: Interpreting Functions: Analyze functions using different representations.

20C552154413416B8C85F51DBCDD2E42.description: Estimate the rate of change from a graph.

9F131C4482E640EF9C88F5F5ADB6704C.description:
For example, if the function h(n) gives the number of person-hours it
takes to assemble n engines in a factory, then the positive integers
would be an appropriate domain for the function.

A2D6E235819C4B338EE3E5A66BE35A2B.description:
Relate the domain of a function that models a real-world scenario to its
graph and identify appropriate numbers (e.g., real, integer, whole) for the
domain.

9533BB1AFAB24CA8AD78D49B4542C721.description:
For a function that models a relationship between two quantities, interpret
key features of graphs, including intercepts and patterns of increase and
decrease.

9D2E7305378640FB85E2BBD10DBF09A0.description: Interpreting Functions: Interpret functions that arise in applications in terms of the context.

E2D59E0569E1409782E8C713DE66375D.description:
For example, for a sequence defined by the rule Add 5 starting at 0,
match the 3rd place with the value 15.

E382EAF7F7E44B6BAF8F3FB6D6F18F38.description: Match the place in a sequence with the value in the sequence.

8320B83C6B29455ABA7F4EBA6C84CC92.description: Evaluate functions for inputs in their domains.

EDA14C87C6454B5DA12E974F2748ECEF.description:
Demonstrate an understanding that a function is a correspondence from
one set to another set.

1CF3808501524F15A63605AF6FBE88DD.description: Interpreting Functions: Understand the concept of a function and use function notation.

2F5D9A281E594AEDACCB48817CDDA2FC.description:
For example, the line d = 50h could represent distance traveled when
moving at 50 miles per hour. The point (2,100) represents traveling 100
miles after 2 hours).

BE50F49277B94CC6BEEDC4AA69954735.description: Interpret the meaning of a point on a graphed line in context.

4C5697FB39974EAC8F29720BFCBBBFC6.description:
Confirm that the point of intersection for a given system of linear equations
is the point that makes both equations true.

AFC30CFBF974487BB92C7B443A7C0195.description: Graph an equation in two variables given a table of values.

8E78F9AE59294E4FBA61B544518FAD14.description: Reasoning with Equations & Inequalities: Represent and solve equations and inequalities graphically.

4E4ECF15DD8E40DF9865FAE0EE12044B.description:
Solve systems of linear equations approximately with graphs, focusing on
pairs of linear equations in two variable.

FBDD7B275FAA47E28DC63EC4FB6513EE.description: Reasoning with Equations & Inequalities: Solve systems of equations.

282A7B9D0C264C0EB4DBEA8C9E8C8DEC.description: Solve linear equations in one variable.

A0077E53ADBF49EFA4D75A49118AEB35.description: Reasoning with Equations & Inequalities: Solve equations and inequalities in one variable.

684D2948AE7148AE8344EE91EC8F9E01.description:
Explain each step in solving a simple given equation involving one or two
operations, such as 3x + 1 = 7 (Step 1), 3x = 6 (Step 2), and x = 2 (Step 3).

7A0AB30362694F2F99A591923FE7AA6E.description: Reasoning with Equations & Inequalities: Understand solving equations as a process of reasoning and explain the reasoning.

18CDBD31F33C4755A16C7ABDA523603B.description:
For example, if the speed limit is 70 miles per hour and you have 4 hours
of travel time, destinations less than or equal to 280 miles away are
going to be possible to reach in that time. Destinations greater than 280
miles away are not.

FBDB720A149945268444A092670AAC89.description: Identify solutions as viable or nonviable options in a modeling context.

D3F335162F3F4302BC30AE386B0E9BFE.description:
Create equations in two variables to represent linear relationships between
quantities and graph equations on coordinate axes with labels and scales.

45F0135F59664AF4B292149E83E45407.description: Include equations arising from linear functions.

966C97825E494330BCC2969845C0B54E.description:
Create equations and inequalities in one variable and use them to solve
problems.

2C393B0CA74A43DFA5AC5658E05DACB5.description: Creating Equations: Create equations that describe numbers or relationships.

6672BA0E9C1E4967800337183D2F577C.description: Arithmetic with Polynomials & Rational Expressions: Rewrite rational expressions.

D77370861AA84050B4568690A3236540.description: Arithmetic with Polynomials & Rational Expressions: Use polynomial identities to solve problems.

6F4DAC8CCEE34AA68E6BD1F17D7F97D6.description: Arithmetic with Polynomials & Rational Expressions: Understand the relationship between zeros and factors of polynomials.

E528174B05654246BC633C424938C6F4.description: Add and subtract first-degree polynomials, i.e., combine like terms.

EB5D32ED936E46ADB0FC0CE7DF56B24F.description: Arithmetic with Polynomials & Rational Expressions: Perform arithmetic operations on polynomials.

F764388A5A3942D09BBFA4441D3F2B8A.description:
Determine the successive term in a geometric sequence given the common
ration (EE.A.SSE.4).

0F28A23765CB485E9165205041F2B49C.description:
For example, 80w + 20w + 200 + 300 might describe earning $80 per
week at one job and $20 per week at another job, as well as one-time
gifts of $200 from a parent and $300 from a grandparent. That could be
re-written in the equivalent form as 100w + 500, which would then help
show the total earned per week ($100) and the sum of the one-time
gifts ($500).

973627DD04444ACAAC9A452E723D3BFF.description:
Choose and produce an equivalent form of a one-variable expression to
reveal and explain properties of the quantity represented by the
expression.

3B18A45B2D4D47C2A6959A93A2C15813.description: Seeing Structure in Expressions: Write expressions in equivalent forms to solve problems.

F3B0F738E1054A72868E59F0F081D4B0.description: For example, 3x can be written as x + x + x.

E1DFF1AC21FF4EBCA304D468DFCEA55F.description: Use the structure of a simple expression to identify ways to rewrite it.

EB8957561FFA4A1BAD63B85C641F9B43.description:
For example, the expression 100w + 500 could represent earning $100
per week (w) and a starting balance of $500.

7A7AD51581E6413EAD13DE383DE312D6.description: Interpret parts of an expression, such as terms, factors, and coefficients.

1CF0BCC932BF4FB5ADF5F138C7145331.description: Interpret expressions that represent a quantity in terms of its context.

5214E3F6B2244C01B2218D6B333A8E96.description: Seeing Structure in Expressions: Interpret the structure of expressions.

90D6C3A429694EB8899081A264D4EA17.description: Vector & Matrix Quantities: Perform operations on matrices and use matrices in applications.

1D39F65E866C4088846592960EF21AD1.description: Vector & Matrix Quantities: Perform operations on vectors.

02032B07C36547D8BEA9FE218081C5CF.description: Vector & Matrix Quantities: Represent and model with vector quantities.

D922C21ABA3843ECBF695A6828E2DFDA.description:
Solve real-world problems with real coefficients that have real number
solutions.

A397EBFEE55C497F881748749588E7A6.description: The Complex Number System: Use complex numbers in polynomial identities and equations.

83A3F2E36DC74814B2933A26135FFC7D.description: The Complex Number System: Represent complex numbers and their operations on the complex plane.

2FEF327C78DF488285A64EC7C64AA932.description:
Use the commutative, associative, and distributive properties to add,
subtract, and multiple real (whole) numbers (EE.C-CN.2.a).

E68CE0BCF959402B9655DDAF622BBBC8.description:
For example, we need the counting numbers to count whole things,
fractions and decimals to represent parts of wholes (or between wholes
on the number line), and negative numbers to represent quantities less
than zero.

E9ACA5124D464406825C6772FFCF496E.description:
Know that different kinds of numbers are needed to represent different
quantities.

7E1CF1F006F3484FAEAE7CEEA142371D.description: The Complex Number System: Perform arithmetic operations with complex numbers.

A0BCC99A4AEB4640BB6BA7B9465CA7D9.description:
For example, students should be able to give an example of when
knowing time to a fraction of a second (like running in a race) versus the
nearest year (like giving your age).

EEB5F6CE71D8410EB186E39D8BA52DA4.description:
Choose a level of accuracy appropriate to limitations on measurement
when reporting quantities.

045B14149E0D487BBB012BDD00C966B9.description:
For example, fuel economy can be described as miles per gallon (instead
of feet per barrel of gasoline) because miles and gallons are the way we
typically measure driving distances and fuel use.

91764450045149F5BE5722FBE7ECE875.description: Define appropriate quantities for the purpose of descriptive modeling.

1EB0F2A053F2474BAA36B306996BEBA4.description:
For example, a problem asking How many eggs will I use today if Im
using half of three dozen eggs today and the other half tomorrow?
requires a student to make sense of dozen either at the beginning (3
dozen is 36 eggs, and half is 18 eggs) or at the end (half of 3 dozen is 1.5
dozen, which is 18 eggs) of their solution.

40476FAB26784DEBAC0F3C5237B5EBFD.description:
Use units as a way to understand problems and to guide the solution of
multi-step problems.

16F1F3D0B9CC4A0EA6AD51EDACAF9A26.description: Quantities: Reason quantitatively and use units to solve problems.

F32504EBC34F4E5D8608D000D8811CE4.description: The Real Number System: Use properties of rational and irrational numbers.

C5C1543ED23D4E96BAAD057AE4140A0D.description:
Rewrite expressions involving whole number exponents using expanded
form, e.g., y3 = y times y times y.

E9305DBC14374ADF97A7470B539321E5.description:
Write and evaluate numerical expressions involving whole-number
exponents of 2 or 3 (squared and cubed).

B6328B3EE1F649879E188A5C3A4D37DF.description: The Real Number System: Extend the properties of exponents to rational exponents.
